Testing how collector biases influence models

Kelley Erickson

February 1, 2019

  1. Simulate reality: true distribution of individuals across Florida

    There are several different ways this could be done:

  • Use the full data set (all years) as “truth” for current county-level distribution. Go backwards in time, removing a certain (variable) percentage of counties from the list of occupied counties at each time step.

  • Start with the counties of origin occupied and assume neighboring unoccupied counties become occupied with a randomly selected probability of colonization each year.

  1. Simulate collector behavior from collectors with a variety of behaviors:
    1. Broad collectors who only collect a species once per county, and never again (in time)
    2. Specialists who collect everything they see of a particular species
    3. Casual opportunistic collectors who only make one collection
    4. Collectors with limited geographical range
    For S. terebinthifolia:

  • What does the distribution of number of collections per county by collector look like? Do collectors tend to only collect a species once per county for all time? Or do they reset every year?

  • What percentage of collectors who collected more than one record are specialists (only collect one species, one genus, one family)? What percentage are generalists?

  • For collectors who collected more than one records, what does the distribution of number of counties surveyed look like?

  • What percentage of records without coordinates are unique (the only record in a county) over all time? Within a year?

  1. Explore scenarios listed in 2 for a range of detectability probabilities
  2. Construct occupancy models:
  1. That do not take collector behavior into account
  2. That include a covariate for collector behavior in models for p
  1. Compare models to reality and assess level of underprediction (or overprediction). **************************************************************************************

There is a discrepancy in the coverage of the Tracheophyta data set and the Anacardiaceae data set. Currently the Anacardiaceae data set contains records with coordinates that are not in the Tracheophyta data set.
